{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598804"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:44:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:44:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15507"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15507"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.15,0.11,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8198"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51282"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcid-base disorders involve primary changes in either carbon dioxide (CO2) or bicarbonate (HCO3-), followed by compensatory mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes an acid-base disorder and its compensation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Respiratory acidosis involves increased PaCO2 and renal retention of HCO3-","Respiratory alkalosis involves decreased PaCO2 and renal retention of HCO3-","Respiratory alkalosis involves increased PaCO2 and renal excretion of HCO3-","Metabolic alkalosis involves decreased HCO3- with increased pH","Metabolic acidosis involves increased HCO3- with decreased pH"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E, elevated PaCO2 leads to decreased pH. The kidneys compensate by retaining (not excreting) HCO3- to help normalize pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E, decreased PaCO2 leads to increased pH. The kidneys compensate by excreting (not retaining) HCO3-. This disorder is caused by hyperventilation, not by increased PaCO2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetabolic alkalosis\u003C/strong\u003E involves increased (not decreased) HCO3- leading to increased pH. \u003Cstrong\u003EMetabolic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E involves decreased (not increased) HCO3- with decreased pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these compensatory mechanisms is crucial for correctly identifying and treating acid-base disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Respiratory acidosis occurs when PaCO2 rises, with kidneys retaining HCO3- to compensate","Respiratory alkalosis occurs when PaCO2 falls, with kidneys excreting HCO3- to compensate","Metabolic alkalosis involves increased HCO3- and increased pH"],"references":["Spindelboeck W, Gemes G, Strasser C, Toescher K, Kores B, Metnitz P, Haas J, Prause G. Arterial blood gases during and their dynamic changes after cardiopulmonary resuscitation: A prospective clinical study. Resuscitation. 2016 Sep;106:24-9. doi: 10.1016/j.resuscitation.2016.06.013. Epub 2016 Jun 18. PMID: 27328890.","Castro D, Patil SM, Zubair M, Keenaghan M. Arterial Blood Gas. 2024 Jan 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725604.","Jeremy Rogers and Mike Cadogan. Blood Gas Interpretation. Life in the Fastlane. 2024. Available from: https://litfl.com/acid-base-disorders/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51282"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15507"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51282"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T09:12:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T09:13:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8198"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedA